d=\"p1\">**</bpt>san<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph>policy.xml<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> file on the disk.","pos":[13128,13203]},{"content":"The following example illustrates this step:","pos":[13204,13248]},{"pos":[14339,14541],"content":"Place the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>san<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph>policy.xml<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> file created in the previous step into the root directory of the Windows partition on the Windows To Go drive (W: from the previous examples) and run the following command:"},{"content":"Create an answer file (unattend.xml) that disables the use of Windows Recovery Environment with Windows To Go.","pos":[14629,14739]},{"content":"You can use the following code sample to create a new answer file or you can paste it into an existing answer file:","pos":[14740,14855]},{"content":"Once the answer file has been saved, copy unattend.xml into the sysprep folder on the Windows To Go drive (for example, W:<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System32<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>sysprep","pos":[15956,16106]},{"pos":[16114,16500],"content":"**Important**  \nSetup unattend files are processed based on their location. Setup will place a temporary unattend file into the **%systemroot%\\\\panther** folder which is the first location that setup will check for installation information. You should make sure that folder does not contain a previous version of an unattend.xml file to ensure that the one you just created is used.","leadings":["","    "],"nodes":[{"content":"Important","pos":[2,11]},{"content":"Setup unattend files are processed based on their location. Setup will place a temporary unattend file into the **%systemroot%\\\\panther** folder which is the first location that setup will check for installation information. You should make sure that folder does not contain a previous version of an unattend.xml file to ensure that the one you just created is used.","pos":[16,382],"nodes":[{"content":"Setup unattend files are processed based on their location.","pos":[0,59]},{"content":"Setup will place a temporary unattend file into the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>%systemroot%<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>panther<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> folder which is the first location that setup will check for installation information.","pos":[60,224]},{"content":"You should make sure that folder does not contain a previous version of an unattend.xml file to ensure that the one you just created is used.","pos":[225,366]}]}]},{"pos":[16506,16766],"content":"If you do not wish to boot your Windows To Go device on this computer and want to remove it to boot it on another PC, be sure to use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Safely Remove Hardware and Eject Media<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> option to safely disconnect the drive before physically removing it from the PC."},{"content":"Your Windows To Go workspace is now ready to be started.","pos":[16775,16831]},{"content":"You can now <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>prepare a host computer<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619165)</ept> using the Windows To Go startup options to test your workspace configuration, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>configure the workspace for offline domain join<ept id=\"p2\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619166)</ept>, or <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>enable BitLocker protection for your Windows To Go drive<ept id=\"p3\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619167)</ept>.","pos":[16832,17208]},{"content":"To prepare a host computer","pos":[17214,17240]},{"content":"Computers running Windows 8 and later can be configured as host computers that use Windows To Go automatically whenever a Windows To Go workspace is available at startup.","pos":[17242,17412]},{"content":"When the Windows To Go startup options are enabled on a host computer, Windows will divert startup to the Windows To Go drive whenever it is attached to the computer.","pos":[17413,17579]},{"content":"This makes it easy to switch from using the host computer to using the Windows To Go workspace.","pos":[17580,17675]},{"content":"Tip","pos":[17679,17682]},{"content":"If you will be using a PC running Windows 7 as your host computer, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Tips for configuring your BIOS settings to work with Windows To Go<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=618951)</ept> for information to help you prepare the host computer.","pos":[17687,17930]},{"content":"If you want to use the Windows To Go workspace, simply shut down the computer, plug in the Windows To Go drive, and turn on the computer.","pos":[17935,18072]},{"content":"To use the host computer, shut down the Windows To Go workspace, unplug the Windows To Go drive, and turn on the computer.","pos":[18073,18195]},{"content":"To set the Windows To Go Startup options for host computers running Windows 10:","pos":[18197,18276]},{"pos":[18282,18367],"content":"Using Cortana, search for <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Windows To Go startup options<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and then press <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Enter<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[18373,18516],"content":"In the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Windows To Go Startup Options<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> dialog box, select <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Yes<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Save Changes<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to configure the computer to boot from USB"},{"content":"For host computers running Windows 8 or Windows 8.1:","pos":[18518,18570]},{"pos":[18576,18677],"content":"Press <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Windows logo key+W<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, search for <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Windows To Go startup options<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, and then press <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Enter<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[18682,18826],"content":"In the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Windows To Go Startup Options<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> dialog box, select <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Yes<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Save Changes<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to configure the computer to boot from USB."},{"content":"You can configure your organization's computers to automatically start from the USB drive by enabling the following Group Policy setting:","pos":[18828,18965]},{"content":"Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Administrative Templates<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>Windows Components<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Portable Operating System<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>Windows To Go Default Startup Options","pos":[18973,19107]},{"content":"After this policy setting is enabled, automatic starting of a Windows To Go workspace will be attempted when a USB drive is connected to the computer when it is started.","pos":[19111,19280]},{"content":"Users will not be able to use the Windows To Go Startup Options to change this behavior.","pos":[19281,19369]},{"content":"If you disable this policy setting, booting to Windows To Go when a USB drive is connected will not occur unless a user configures the option manually in the firmware.","pos":[19370,19537]},{"content":"If you do not configure this policy setting, users who are members of the Administrators group can enable or disable booting from a USB drive using the Windows To Go Startup Options.","pos":[19538,19720]},{"content":"Your host computer is now ready to boot directly into Windows To Go workspace when it is inserted prior to starting the computer.","pos":[19722,19851]},{"content":"Optionally you can perform <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configure Windows To Go workspace for offline domain join<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619169)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Enable BitLocker protection for your Windows To Go drive<ept id=\"p2\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=619152)</ept>.","pos":[19852,20100]},{"content":"Booting your Windows To Go workspace","pos":[20106,20142]},{"content":"After you have configured your host PC to boot from USB, you can use the following procedure to boot your Windows To Go workspace:","pos":[20144,20274]},{"content":"To boot your workspace","pos":[20278,20300]},{"content":"Make sure that the host PC is not in a sleep state.","pos":[20308,20359]},{"content":"If the computer is in a sleep state, either shut it down or hibernate it.","pos":[20360,20433]},{"content":"Insert the Windows To Go USB drive directly into a USB 3.0 or USB 2.0 port on the PC.","pos":[20439,20524]},{"content":"Do not use a USB hub or extender.","pos":[20525,20558]},{"content":"Turn on the PC.","pos":[20564,20579]},{"content":"If your Windows To Go drive is protected with BitLocker you will be asked to type the password, otherwise the workspace will boot directly into the Windows To Go workspace.","pos":[20580,20752]},{"content":"Advanced deployment steps","pos":[20757,20782]},{"content":"The following steps are used for more advanced deployments where you want to have further control over the configuration of the Windows To Go drives, ensure that they are correctly configured for remote access to your organizational resources, and have been protected with BitLocker Drive Encryption.","pos":[20785,21085]},{"content":"Configure Windows To Go workspace for remote access","pos":[21091,21142]},{"content":"Making sure that Windows To Go workspaces are effective when used off premises is essential to a successful deployment.","pos":[21144,21263]},{"content":"One of the key benefits of Windows To Go is the ability for your users to use the enterprise managed domain joined workspace on an unmanaged computer which is outside your corporate network.","pos":[21264,21454]},{"content":"To enable this usage, typically you would provision the USB drive as described in the basic deployment instructions and then add the configuration to support domain joining of the workspace, installation of any line-of-business applications, and configuration of your chosen remote connectivity solution such as a virtual private network client or DirectAccess.","pos":[21455,21816]},{"content":"Once these configurations have been performed the user can work from the workspace using a computer that is off-